snippet.textDisplay:
I’m at 18:32 rn and I have one thing to point out. “MatPat, you might think your channel is small, but you have quite a wide reach (beyond your subscriber-base) and even more people that don’t watch your content still get your topics related to them. By pointing out YouTube TV’s edge in the game, you kinda took away that edge: YTV gets ahead by staying the little guy. They can easily get content from other sources and benefit from advertising their competitors, because most people don’t think of them as being a streaming service. They don’t need to even: their parent, YouTube, started by advertising as a streaming service in the days when streaming was very different than it is now. YouTube got big and doesn’t need to advertise as such anymore. When YTV came along, it was just a paid version of the original with some higher-end productions. It’s pretty clever. You can’t be kicked out the game by anyone if they don’t know you’re in the game.

LOVE your content btw. Please bring back GameLab 🙏🏾

snippet.textDisplay: Yeah, streaming is just cable tv but updated for a modern audience, what else is new? Surprised we took so long to figure that out, back when tv was first created nobody knew what they wanted to watch and tv was a secondary part of their primarily social and business lives. Nowadays with internet celebrities , more and more lives become primarily about TV and entertainment, ppl no longer tune in late at night to catch w/e before they go to sleep, they actively look for the next big thing, and thus Movies/series on demand became a thing, we no longer want to see just whatever, we want to see Rick and Morty (for example) right now, to catch up on what our friends are talking about.

Nice save MatPat. I was all fired up to berate you for shilling for YouTube TV until you scratched the record when you hit the pricing. And I 100% agree with your conclusion. They have us all by the orbs and all we can do is pay up or opt out.

The one thing I could say about cable was at least you could get all your content in a single location. Siloing streaming content requires maintaining multiple subscriptions at a price for each. And remembering which show is on which platform all the time gets tedious.

snippet.textDisplay: If the TV and movie studios think I'm going to pay more for less, they have another thing coming. There is no winner in this scenario. They will all continue to lose ground together, as people just stop caring about what they have to sell anymore. Movies and TV are becoming less interesting. So the winner is: none of them. It's Youtube and social media. Who needs a TV service or streaming channel when you don't spend your time watching TV at all? Want to win me back? Stop the infighting, combine all content on one service, drop the price, and go back to producing apolitical fun content. Otherwise, I and everyone else will just continue to pirate what I want to watch and happily ignore the rest.

snippet.textDisplay:
There is a demographic that wasn't covered, but I think anyone who saw my name would know that: the anime community.

You want to talk about the Netflix of anime, Crunchyroll? They literally do everything Netflix does: is one of the first in anime streaming, has a large library, now has contenders with their exclusives that have taken away from the platform (Netflix included here), and uses their money to make original content woth varying amounts of success. They also have an easy to use video player (much better IMHO than Hulu, Funimation, Hidive, etc).
